<section>
    <header>Home Winemaking General Info</header>
    <div class="laff-section-copy">
		<p>Wine Yeasts (From Vines to Wines p134-135)</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Montrachet (UC-Davis 522). Concerns about hydrogen sulfide production. Most common.</li>
			<li>Pasteur Champagne (UC-Davis 595). What Jeff Cox generally recommends.</li>
			<li>California Champagne (UC-Davis 505)</li>
			<li>Epernay 2</li>
			<li>Flor Sherry (UC-Davis 519)</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Measurements</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Brix (starting, pre-fermentation)</li>
			<li>TA (Titratable Acidity)</li>
			<li>pH</li>
			<li>Residual Sugar (post-fermentation)</li>
			<li>Total SO_2 (added during the process)</li>
			<li>Percent Alcohol (post-fermentation)</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Aging: all ages are after the final racking (1-6 months depending on process used). The first racking is immediately following primary fermentation. Second immediately following secondary fermentation (2-3 months later). Third after the leese settles (another 3 months).
			(From Vines to Wines p159-160, p172)
		</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Big Reds: 12 months minimum. </li>
			<li>Light Reds: 6-12 months. Most drinkable from 12-24 months of age.</li>
			<li>Full-favlored whites (Chardonnay): 6-12 months.</li>
			<li>Light, fruity whites: 3-6 months of aging</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Aging environment: try to shoot for 10-16&deg; celsius, but 10-18&deg; celsius is good. Should be dark, sunlight will compromise the alcohol. Avoid temperature swings. After bottling you want a flat 14&deg; celsius temperature ideally.
		</p>
		<p>Optimum serving temperatures (From Vines to Wines p180)</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Big Reds: 16-18&deg; celsius</li>
			<li>Light red wines: 13-16&deg; celsius</li>
			<li>Robust white wines: 13-16&deg; celsius</li>
			<li>Light white wines: 10-13&deg; celsius</li>
			<li>Champagne: 4-7&deg; celsius</li>
		</ul>
		<p>
			Final alcohol content golden standard is 12-12.5%. 11% is acceptable, but should be higher. Always try to get at least 11%. Wine yeasts generally work up to 15% alcohol as an upper-limit (Vines to Wines, p119)
		</p>
    </div>
</section>
<section>
	<header>Sulfite (SO_2)</header>
    <div class="laff-section-copy">
		<p>Sulfite is used to free wine must of wild yeasts that could infect wine. It can cause headaches, flushed feelings, or other reactions. You want to minimize the amount of Sulfite you add to wine. The FDA allows up to 350 ppm of sulfite in wine. California poses an upper limit of 175 ppm in reds and 225 ppm in whites (Vines to Wines, p119)</p>
		<p>Cox recommends 50ppm for reds and 70ppm for whites of potassium metabisulfite to prevent wild yeasts and limit undesirable characteristics. This is for musts with a pH of 3.2 for whites and 3.5 for reds. (Lower pH is higher acidity, pH of 7 is neutral)</p>
		<p>1 Campden tablet will raise one gallon to 50ppm of sulfite.</p>
		<p>Measure your pH and adjust your sulfite accordingly. Higher pH means more sulfite is needed (and vice-versa). Vines to Wines p122 has a handy chart.</p>
	</div>
</section>
