	<header>Brix &amp; Specific Gravity (Vines to Wines p99, p124-125)</header>
    <div class="laff-section-copy">
		<p><a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brix">Brix</a> is an imprecise measurement because a Wine Must has other solids disolved into it besides sugar. Brix itself is defined as "One degree brix is one gram sucrose in 100 grams solution".</p>
		<p>Home Winemakers traditionally use "Specific Gravity" to measure the potential sugar / ripeness / potential alcohol of the must. This isn't the most scientific measurement, but seems to be relatively accurate.</p>
		<p>Refractometers are great before alcohol is created but are inaccurate once alcohol is in the mixture</p>
		<p>Hydrometers assume a temperature of 15-16&deg; celsius. Temperature deviations should be accounted for in S.G./Brix measurement.</p>
		<p>Hydrometeres are measured at the base of the liquid, not the sides. Liquids creep up the sides -- you don't want that.</p>
		<p>Ideally your S.G. measurement is accurate to 4 significant figures, but this can be hard to achieve.</p>
